I believe I discovered the root cause of the problem.  It looks like any class method where there are extra arguments, if that method is decorated with @gen.coroutine then the route is not built properly.  For example from the helloworld demo:

```python
    class Greeting(APIHandler):
        @schema.validate(...)
        def get(self, fname, lname):
```
This will return the correct route:

    ".../greeting/(?P<fname>[a-zA-Z0-9_]+)/(?P<lname>[a-zA-Z0-9_]+)/?$", 
    "<class 'helloworld.Greeting'>"

If you modify that method to make it async:

```python
    class Greeting(APIHandler):
        @schema.validate(...)
        @gen.coroutine
        def get(self, fname, lname):
```

Then in this instance, the route will break:

    "/greeting/?", 
    "<class 'helloworld.Greeting'>"

Hi @joykrogers -- it looks like the problem here is invalid JSON, specifically a single misplaced comma (oops!):

Specifically the comma that should have been at the closing brace before "id":"matthew" was instead after `"url": "http://www.mwop.net"}`

Once corrected like so, it will parse correctly:
```json
{
    "_links": {
        "self": {
            "href": "http://example.org/api/user/matthew"
        }
    },
    "id": "matthew",
    "name": "Matthew Weier O'Phinney",
    "_embedded": {
        "contacts": [
            {
                "_links": {
                    "self": {
                        "href": "http://example.org/api/user/mac_nibblet"
                    }
                },
                "id": "mac_nibblet",
                "name": "Antoine Hedgecock"
            },
            {
                "_links": {
                    "self": {
                        "href": "http://example.org/api/user/spiffyjr"
                    }
                },
                "id": "spiffyjr",
                "name": "Kyle Spraggs"
            }
        ],
        "website": {
            "_links": {
                "self": {
                    "href": "http://example.org/api/locations/mwop"
                }
            },
            "id": "mwop",
            "url": "http://www.mwop.net"
        }
    }
}
```

It looks like the issue is present in the original too -- whoops!  http://phlyrestfully.readthedocs.org/en/latest/halprimer.html

You can test this in the python like so, after saving the corrected json to 'jsondoc.json':

```python
json_text = open('jsondoc.json').read()
json_obj = json.loads(json_text)
query1 = '_links.self.href'
query2 = 'id'
query3 = '_embedded.contacts.0._links.self.href'
pyresttest.validators.MiniJsonExtractor.query_dictionary(query1, json_obj)
pyresttest.validators.MiniJsonExtractor.query_dictionary(query2, json_obj)
pyresttest.validators.MiniJsonExtractor.query_dictionary(query3, json_obj)
```

Output:
```
>>> json_text = open('jsondoc.json').read()
>>> json_obj = json.loads(json_text)
>>> query1 = '_links.self.href'
>>> query2 = 'id'
>>> query3 = '_embedded.contacts.0._links.self.href'
>>> pyresttest.validators.MiniJsonExtractor.query_dictionary(query1, json_obj)
u'http://example.org/api/user/matthew'
>>> pyresttest.validators.MiniJsonExtractor.query_dictionary(query2, json_obj)
u'matthew'
>>> pyresttest.validators.MiniJsonExtractor.query_dictionary(query3, json_obj)
u'http://example.org/api/user/mac_nibblet'
```

You should see some errors in the PyRestTest output due to the invalid JSON input here. 
Side note: the trailing comma after the closing brace is against the JSON spec but *some* parsers in browsers silently ignore it (Python doesn't). 

Thanks for using PyRestTest, and I hope that answers your question?

Cheers,
Sam

