@robwebset If you will notice I was merely discussing alternatives. The first alternative would branch of and essentially pull support at some future point in time, i.e. **not now**. The second alternative would maintain support, but simply depend on manual testing for support to be included in the release.

With regards to previous decisions, yes, we have had this discussion recently, and I did then, and will continue to respect the groups decision. However, with regards to what have changed, well;

 * Several of tools that we depend on, have now finally pulled the plug on support for this 6+ year old version of python, a tendency which I do not think will slow down, which will make it ever increasingly more difficult to maintain properly
 * And of lesser importance, we then now learn, that the main user of the 2.6 support is the plugin system of a program that don't really care about its plugins to begin with, which kind of suck (and also, as far as I understand, did the whole plugin system wrong to begin with, essentially including python in the application, instead of including the application in python).

Do not misunderstand me (no need to get defensive), I care about this project, and of maintaining it in a somewhat professional way, so that users know they can depend on it, so obviously we should not go and add and pull support for python versions on a whim. We decided to add it, and I stand by that, and so I don't think we should remove the support again before it becomes necessary or the need for it has vanished. **But** we do need to reconsider this position when new stuff happens and that so happens to be pretty quickly.

PS: Just on a side note. As I remember the discussion about adding 2.6 support in the first place, at least one of the proponents was also suggesting that the support would be time limited and that the purpose would be to give you a **newer** version to work with (not indefinite support), which is pretty close to my first alternative.

